Explaining alcohol effects on academic performence using SHAP¶

Task A¶

In this homework I'll explain performance of portugeese students (secondary education). The dataset will not differ from the the previous homework.

  1. Train a tree-based ensemble model on the selected dataset; it can be one of random forest, GBM, CatBoost, XGBoost, LightGBM (various types) etc.
  2. Select two observations from the dataset and calculate the model's prediction.
  3. Next, for the same observations, calculate the decomposition of predictions, so-called variable attributions, using SHAP from two packages of choice, e.g. for Python: dalex and shap, for R: DALEX and iml.
  4. Find any two observations in the dataset, such that they have different variables of the highest importance, e.g. age and gender have the highest (absolute) attribution for observation A, but race and class are more important for observation B.
  5. (If possible) Select one variable X and find two observations in the dataset such that for one observation, X has a positive attribution, and for the other observation, X has a negative attribution.
  6. (How) Do the results differ across the two packages selected in point (3)?
  7. (Using one explanation package of choice) Train another model of any class: neural network, linear model, decision tree etc. and find an observation for which SHAP attributions are different between this model and the one trained in point (1).
  8. Comment on the results obtained in points (4)-(7)

ad. 1.

This time I've decided not to join math and portugeese dataset, but to do separate models and check if there are any noticible differences in explanations between them. All categorical variables were one-hot-encoded due to problems with libraries. I've used xgboost model from xgboost library.

ad. 2.

I've chosen observations randomly (and hardcoded in code so that it still remains reproducable). What is worth observing is the difference in distributions of academic performance on math and portugeese.

Math:

Portugeese:

After plotting thoses distributions I was sure that checking that dataset separetly was better than joining them due to shift in distribution (it was probably easier to get a good mark in portugeese than in math).

ad. 4.

  • For math dataset

We can see that for sample 0 three most important features (absolute values) from shap packagew are Dalc (workday alcohol consumption), absences and free time. It's worth mentioning that Dalc in this case is rather low (2 in scale up to 5), absences are low (1 in scale up to 93) and freetime is high (4 in scale up to 5). Absences and freetime have negative value.

In the second sample we have age (equal 18), goout (4 in scale up to 5) and absences (4).

Only absences are in the first three features (conclusion: if you want to have good grades don't ommit math classes!)

In dalex package the features are different -- in the first sample (health, absences, failures), in the second (absences, age, failures)

  • For portugeese dataset

From shap package we have: for the first sample (health, Walc -- weekend alcohol consumption, studytime), for the second sample (Dalc, guardian_other, health). We can see that health is important in both cases but other features are compeletly different.

From dalex package: for the first sample (failures, school_MS, freetime), for the second sample (guardian_other, failures, freetime)

ad. 5.

Quick example here. Let's take sample 2 from math dataset and one new observation from this dataset. The feature romantic_yes is positive in one sample and negative in the other.

ad. 6.

The most important thing is that they differ in shaply values. I guess that both of them are sampled shapley values so they may have different ways of sampling instances.

They also differ in a method of plotting the results.

ad. 7.

I've used dalex package for the first observation of math dataset. The second model I've used was SVM. By looking at the shap values, I can see that SVM may not be the best model for this task.

The only value that matters for the SVM model is health. Explanation from xgboost model is reacher, more complex and more informative (in context of explaining model's decision).

ad. 8. Done :)

Task B¶

Calculate Shapley values for player A given the following value function

v() = 0
v(A) = 20
v(B) = 20
v(C) = 60
v(A,B) = 60
v(A,C) = 70
v(B,C) = 70
v(A,B,C) = 100

Solution:

$\phi_A = \frac{1}{6} \cdot \left(2 \cdot 20 + 40 + 10 + 2 \cdot 30 \right) = 25$

Explanaition:

  • When A is the first in the group it brings 20 to the group. We have two cases like that (ABC, ACB)
  • When B is first in the group and A is second we have: $60 - 20 = 40$
  • When C is first in the group and A is second we have: $70 - 60 = 10$
  • When A is the last one in the group we have: $100 - 70 = 30$. We have two cases like that (BCA, CBA).

In [177]:
def get_one_hot_columns(df):
  one_hot_columns = []
  for column in df.columns:
    if df[column].dtype == 'object':
      one_hot_columns.append(column)
  return one_hot_columns
In [178]:
